s book are based on transcripts of classroom interaction in nine different countries. In each chapter, the first author explains the specific context and through a theoretical and/or experiential perspective interprets the transcript data. The data are then re-interpreted by other authors in the book, illustrating the complexity and richness of interpretation and creating a dialogue among the book’s contributors. At the end of each chapter, readers are then invited with assistance to join in the conversation by providing their own interpretations of other transcript data from the same context. The book will be useful for student teachers or practicing professionals, as well as all educators interested in exploratory classroom research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aClassroom environmentvCross-cultural studies. 0aClassroom environmentxCross-cultural studies. 0aCommunication and educationvCross-cultural studies. 0aCommunication and educationxCross-cultural studies. 0aEnglish languagexCross-cultural studiesxStudy and teachingxForeign speakers. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign speakersvCross-cultural studies. 0aInteraction analysis in educationvCross-cultural studies. 0aInteraction analysis in educationxCross-cultural studies. 0aLanguage and educationvCross-cultural studies. 0aLanguage and educationxCross-cultural studies. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Study & Teaching.2bisacsh  aclassroom interaction.  aclassroom transcripts.  acommunities of learning.  acultural practices.  ainterpretive process.  alanguage education.  alanguage teachers.1 aAnderson, Fred E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Roger, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.g